Agriculture, Ecosystems & Environment

Volume 311, 1 May 2021, 107316

Ant community responses to farmland use and revegetation in a fragmented agricultural landscape

Author links open overlay panelKatherinaNgaSomayehNowrouzibKyran M.StauntoncdPhilipBartonaeDon A.Driscollf
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.agee.2021.107316Get rights and content

Highlights

â€¢

Intensive agriculture led to increased homogenisation of the ant community.

â€¢

Revegetation plantings appear to reverse those effects within seven years.

â€¢

A dominant ant species in remnant patches likely increased community divergence.

â€¢

Revegetation near remnant patches can reduce homogenisation of ant communities.

Abstract

Recent alarming losses of insects from agricultural landscapes in multiple countries around the world have brought into sharp focus the urgent need to identify ways to manage these landscapes to avoid further biodiversity decline. Identifying the drivers of insect declines, such as land use change, is critical to this effort. We examined ant communities at the interface between remnant vegetation patches and three adjoining farmland types (wheat crop, rested from cropping and restoration plantings) in a fragmented landscape in temperate Australia. We asked: do ant communities and occurrence of individual species differ between remnant patches and farmlands with more intensive farmland use (restoration plantings < rested farmlands < wheat crop)? We recorded 13,283 ants belonging to 102 species from 30 genera. Excluding 21 singletons, 27 species only occurred in remnant patches compared to ten species found only in farmlands. Ant community composition in wheat crop and rested farmlands significantly differed from their adjacent remnant patches and were more homogeneous. In contrast, ant communities from restoration plantings in farmland were not significantly different in composition from those in the adjacent remnant patch. The large, aggressive Australian meat ant (Iridomyrmex purpureus) showed significantly higher occurrence in the remnant patch than all farmland types, and we suggest that the absence of this strongly interacting species from farmlands may have contributed to biotic homogenisation. Our findings show that native vegetation provides crucial habitat resources for many ant species that are not provided by farmlands, and native plantings can, in some cases, ameliorate negative effects of farmland clearing over relatively short time scales (<7 years). Agricultural intensification that involves loss of remnant native vegetation or reduced revegetation will contribute to ongoing losses and changes to ant biodiversity in farming landscapes. However, replanting native vegetation can lead to rapid restoration, signifying a possible simple remedy to insect declines.

1. Introduction

Given the alarming global statistics about the loss of insects from some agricultural landscapes around the world (Cardoso et al., 2020; Hallmann et al., 2017; Lister and Garcia, 2018; SÃ¡nchez-Bayo and Wyckhuys, 2019), it is now important to evaluate insect diversity in a range of countries to better understand the extent of the losses. While this accounting is vital, moving beyond counting the declines to understanding the mechanisms leading to the losses is also required. If particular landscape features promote insect diversity and help them remain functional in agricultural landscapes, it could provide a management solution to prevent or reduce declines (Dalle Laste et al., 2019; Harvey et al., 2020; Samways et al., 2020).

Agriculture has led to the erosion of insect diversity at local- and landscape-levels mainly through habitat reduction and fragmentation (Benton et al., 2002; Ollerton et al., 2014; Potts et al., 2010). Conversion of land to agriculture directly reduces the extent of native habitat and is a leading cause of biodiversity loss (Lichtenberg et al., 2017; MacDougall et al., 2013). Further intensification of agricultural areas can have far-reaching indirect impacts on remaining native habitats. Intensification can promote invasion by pasture species (Driscoll et al., 2014), and flourishing of generalist or exotic species in intensively farmed areas can promote biotic homogenisation and associated biodiversity loss (Driscoll et al., 2013; Sweaney et al., 2014). However, there are also many native species, such as generalists and disturbance specialists, that are able to exploit resources in novel habitats (Driscoll et al., 2013). Identifying appropriate management practices within farmlands that minimise edge effects and maintain native communities, for example through revegetation or fallowing, is therefore important for combatting biodiversity loss across agricultural landscapes (Cunningham et al., 2013; Samways et al., 2020).

Ants comprise a major component of biodiversity in many agricultural landscapes in terms of their abundance, species richness, and the ecosystem services they provide such as pest management, soil turnover, pollination, and nutrient cycling (Abensperg-Traun et al., 1996; De Bruyn, 1999; Del Toro et al., 2012; Greenslade and Greenslade, 1984; Lach et al., 2010). Australia has a considerable number of ant species by world standards (over 10,000 species; Andersen, 2016), with many new species yet to be discovered or described (Hoffmann, 2010). The ecology of most species is poorly understood, particularly in modified landscapes where the impacts of agricultural land use changes are largely unknown (Andersen et al., 2004; Barton et al., 2016; Hoffmann and Andersen, 2003). Significant advances in knowledge have been made using ants as bioindicators of landscape disturbance (Andersen and Majer, 2004; De Bruyn, 1999). Yet, many studies are limited to remnant patches of native habitats or specific fields at a local farm scale, and rarely cover multiple land uses at a landscape scale (Abensperg-Traun et al., 1996; De Bruyn, 1999; Majer and Beeston, 1996; Ng et al., 2017). Consequently, we have a poor knowledge of how landscapes might be managed to promote and conserve ant biodiversity.

In this study, we compared ant assemblages from remnant patches of vegetation with assemblages from adjoining farmland types which were either (at the time of sampling) wheat crops, rested from cropping or restoration plantings. Our study was conducted in a highly fragmented mixed-farming landscape in temperate south-eastern Australia. We asked the question: Do ant assemblages and species occurrence differ between remnant patches and adjacent farmlands, and does this difference increase with more intense use of farmland (restoration plantings < rested farmland < cropped farmland)?

We predicted that more structurally and floristically complex habitats with lower intensity of use would support higher ant species richness and higher community heterogeneity (i.e. remnant patch > restoration plantings > rested farmland > cropping farmland). Adjoining farmland type might further influence ant responses in the remnant patch in proportion to intensity of farmland use. Our study therefore aims to help improve knowledge of the effects of agricultural intensification on insects, which is a critical step in recognising causes of declines and potential solutions.

2. Materials and methods

2.1. Study area

The study was conducted in a highly cleared and fragmented, temperate, mixed grazingâ€“cropping landscape in the New South Wales Lachlan River Catchment, south-eastern Australia. Widespread clearing for agriculture has restricted native Eucalyptus woodland patches to infertile steeper areas. Many remnant patches have also been modified by livestock grazing, weed invasion, and altered fire regimes (Norris and Thomas, 1991). Our study comprised ten sites that were clustered across three regions; east (2 sites), mid (4 sites) and west (4 sites). The locations ranged from -34.036 S, 146.363 E; -33.826 S, 147.855 E; to -34.411 S, 148.499 E (Fig. 1).

2.2. Sampling

We used a split-plot sampling design, with each of the ten sites containing a remnant Eucalyptus woodland patch with areas (crop-patch, rested-patch, planting-patch) that adjoined three farmland types respectively: wheat crop (crop-farmland), rested crop paddock in fallow, grazed by sheep or cattle (rested-farmland), and restoration plantings <7 years old and fenced from livestock (planting-farmland). The ten remnant patches [patch size 4010 ha +/- 486.4 ha (mean +/- SE)] were selected on the basis that they were Eucalyptus woodland communities with high ground-, mid- and over-storey native vegetation complexity (see Fig. 1; details on habitat and vegetation condition in Ng et al., 2018b). In each site, we sampled ants using pitfall stations placed 200 m in the remnant patch and 200 m in the farmland (measured along a 400 m transect across the remnant patchâ€“farmland interface) over 14 days between October and November 2014. A pitfall station comprised two clear, uncovered plastic pitfall traps (6.5 cm diameter, 250 ml) placed on either side of a drift fence (60 cm long x10 cm high). Traps were buried in the ground with the rim level with the soil surface, and filled with 100 ml of 1:3 glycolâ€“water mixture. The traps were collected at the end of the 14 days of trapping period and inspected at the end of the first week.

Ant samples were preserved in 70 % ethanol. All ants were sorted to morpho-species following Shattuck (2000), and where possible named through comparison with identified specimens held in the CSIRO Tropical Ecosystems Research Centre ant collection, referring to the latest ant nomenclature. A full set of voucher specimens were deposited in the CSIRO Ant Lab collection.

2.3. Analyses

We pooled ant samples from the two pitfall traps in each of the 60 stations to give one sample per station for statistical analyses. We converted count data to absence-presence for species-level analyses. Presence-absence is recommended over abundance when studying pitfall-trapped ant species data because abundances for some species can be spuriously inflated for traps that are located near ant nests (Yeeles et al., 2017).

We examined the composition of ant assemblages using four multivariate approaches. First, we used non-metric multidimensional scaling (nMDS) to visualise overall differences in ant species composition (presence/absence data, singletons omitted) between the remnant patch and adjoining farmland types (crop, rested and planting), using the vegan R package's metaMDS function (Oksanen et al., 2013) and SÃ¸rensen dissimilarities among samples (Clarke, 1993).

Second, we tested for differences in ant composition among the three farmland types and among the remnant patch, separating patches by their adjacent farmland type, giving six groups: crop-farmland, rested-farmland, plantings-farmland, remnant patch beside crop (crop-patch), remnant patch beside rested (rested-patch), remnant patch beside planting (planting-patch). To do this we used permutational multivariate analysis of variance (PERMANOVA), based on SÃ¸rensen dissimilarities and 999 permutations, and with P-values adjusted using sequential Bonferroni corrections to account for multiple comparisons. We used the pairwise.adonis function based on the vegan package (Martinez Arbizu, 2019), and the multcompView package's multcompLetters function to present pairwise comparisons as letters (Graves et al., 2015).

Significant results in PERMANOVA might be due to dissimilarity differences between the six above-mentioned groups (differences between the groupâ€™s centroid location in multivariate space), or differences in the within-category dispersion (mean distance to group centroid), or both. To determine if a significant PERMANOVA result is due to differences between categories (likely turnover) or differences within categories (likely nestedness), we performed an additional permutational analysis of multivariate dispersions (PERMDISP) (Anderson, 2006; Anderson et al., 2006). We ran PERMDISP with 999 permutations, among the six above-mentioned groups (transect-habitat pairs) and tested for pairwise differences using functions betadisper and permutest in the vegan package (Oksanen et al., 2013). We interpreted our findings as follows: a significant result for PERMANOVA but not PERMDISP indicates there are differences due to species turnover, but a significant result for PERMANOVA and PERMDISP indicates there may be differences due to both species turnover and nestedness (Anderson et al., 2011). We used Tukeyâ€™s HSD test based on Brayâ€“Curtis dissimilarities to identify pair-wise differences in ant communities between the six groups (transect-habitat pairs) where the PERMDISP results were significant.

To determine which speciesâ€™ occurrence significantly contributed to any compositional differences between the six groups of transect-habitat pairs, we conducted Dufrene-Legendre indicator species analysis over the absence-presence data (DufrÃªne and Legendre, 1997) to identify ant species fidelity to the different habitat types in two ways: (1) comparing between the remnant patch and all farmland types combined, and (2) comparing between the six groups of transect-habitat pairs. We tested for IndVal significance using a random reallocation procedure with 1000 permutations using the indval function in the labdsv package, and IndVal values > 0.3 and P < 0.05 were inferred as strong indicators (Roberts, 2010).

Finally, we examined species richness of ant community as well as the occurrence (presence/absence) of abundant ant species using generalized linear mixed-effect models (GLMMs), with the glmer function in the lme4 package (Bates et al., 2015). The purpose of our latter analysis was to identify the effects of 'habitat', effects of 'transect', or interactive effects of 'transect' and 'habitat'. We fitted 'site' and 'farmland-patch pair' associated with the transect as nested random effects (1|site/'farmland-patch pair') to account for the non-independent spatial structure of the study design. To control for possible effects of region (three levels: east, mid, west), we included that as an additive fixed effect. We used a Poisson distribution with log link function for species richness count data, and a binomial distribution with a logit link function for presence-absence response variables of individual species. We then checked model fit by examining residual and fitted plots, and checked for overdispersion by dividing the Pearson goodness-of-fit statistic by the residual degrees of freedom and ensuring values were below one (McCullagh and Nelder, 1989). Where there was evidence of overdispersion, we fitted individual-level random effects (Maindonald and Braun, 2006). We used Wald tests (Anova function in the car package (Fox et al., 2013)) to identify the statistical significance of fixed effects and pairwise post hoc Tukey-Kramer tests (glht function in the multcomp package (Hothorn et al., 2008)) to evaluate between-treatment response differences.

3. Results

We sampled 13,283 ants, consisting of 102 species across 30 genera (21 singleton species) (Appendix S1). The most abundant genera sampled were: Iridomyrmex (n = 8,218, 11 species), Pheidole (n = 1,845, 9 species), Monomorium (n = 1,064, 12 species) and Rhytidoponera (n = 1,029, 4 species). The species with the greatest abundance included Iridomyrmex nr. chasei (n = 7026), Pheidole sp. P2. pyriformis gp. (n = 1028), Rhytidoponera metallica (n = 986), Monomorium sp. S1 sordidum gp. (n = 895), Iridomyrmex purpureus (n = 809).

Of the 102 species we collected, we found that 27 species only occurred in remnant patches (when excluding singletons at each site), 10 species only occurred in farmland, and 44 species were found across both habitat types. Within the farmland, two species were only recorded in crop farmland (Monomorium sp. R1 rothsteini gp., Rhytidoponera nr. victoriae), two species only occurred in rested farmland (Doleromyrma sp. A, Tetramorium sp. IB impressum gp.), and three species only occurred in plantings (Hypoponera sp. B, Pheidole sp. V2 variabilis gp., Iridomyrmex nr. splendens) (Appendix S1).

NMDS ordination showed a difference in ant assemblage composition between the remnant patch and crop farmland, and between the remnant patch and rested farmland (Fig. 2). Ant compositional changes were differentiated along NMDS axis 1 from the crop and rested farmlands at low values, through the planting farmland, the remnant patch adjoining plantings, to the remnant patches adjoining crop and rested farmlands at high values (Fig. 3).

PERMANOVA tests confirmed significant compositional differences between the rested farmland and its adjoining remnant patch (rested-patch) (adjusted P = 0.015), and between the crop farmland and its adjoining remnant patch (crop-patch) (adjusted P = 0.015). Ant community composition was not significantly different between the planting farmland and its adjoining remnant patch (planting-patch) (adjusted P = 1.000; Table 1).

PERMDISP showed significant differences in the dispersion (variation among samples within groups) of ant communities between the rested farmland and adjoining patch (P = 0.004), and between the crop farmland and adjoining remnant patch (P = 0.007) (Table 1). These results indicate that the differences in ant communities between the crop and remnant patch, and between the rested farmland and remnant patch, are likely due to nestedness as well as turnover. In particular, multivariate dispersion (among-sample variability) was significantly lower in the crop-farmland and rested-farmland compared with crop-patch (P = 0.004) and rested-patch (P = 0.029), respectively (Fig. 3). Multivariate dispersion was comparable between the planting-farmland and the planting-patch (P = 0.607), and among the remnant patches adjoining the three different farmland types: crop-patch, rested-patch and planting-patch (P > 0.181; Fig. 3). Tukeyâ€™s HSD post hoc test of PERMDISP differences showed lower among-sample variability in the crop farmland than its adjoining remnant patch (Table 1).

Iridomyrmex purpureus was a significant indicator species in terms of their presence in the remnant patch compared to farmlands (all types). Pheidole sp. P2 pyriformis gp. and Nylanderia sp. A were significant indicator species in farmlands compared to the remnant patch (Appendix S2).

GLMM analyses showed that overall ant species richness did not vary significantly among habitat (remnant patch vs. farmland) or among the different farmland types (P > 0.140) (Table S1a). When assessing the occurrence of individual species using GLMM, only I. purpureus showed significant habitat effects (P = 0.014); it occurred in approximately half of the remnant patches compared with only 10 % of the farmland sites (Appendix S3; Appendix S4).

4. Discussion

We found lower variability (lower dispersion) in ant community composition, as well as relatively lower number of unique species, in crop and rested farmlands compared to remnant patches. These findings can be explained by reduced habitat structure, food resources and microclimatic range in cultivated farmlands (Andersen, 1995; Ekroos et al., 2010; Ng et al., 2018a, b; Pereyra et al., 2019; Yates et al., 2012), and the biotic influence of a dominant ant species in remnant patches (Greenslade, 1976). Removal and modification of native vegetation are the primary drivers of the loss of many insect species (Cardoso et al., 2020; Hobbs et al., 2018). Finding a combination of significant differences in community dispersion within groups (transect-habitat pairs), as well as spatial turnover and convergence in community composition, suggests homogenisation of ant assemblages in cultivated farmlands with more generalist species such as strong dispersers and disturbance-tolerant species becoming more common (McKinney and Lockwood, 1999). Long-term studies indicate limited adaptability of many insect species to intensified agricultural practices characterised by monocropping, high soil disturbance (Abensperg-Traun et al., 1996; LÃ¶vei and Sunderland, 1996; Stinner and House, 1990) and agrochemical use (Cunningham et al., 2013; Goulson et al., 2015; Sutcliffe et al., 2015; Tscharntke et al., 2005). These intensive agricultural practices are typical of broad acre cropping in southern Australia.

Our remnant patches are associated with strong environmental spatial heterogeneity that can shape insect community structure at a patch level (Gibb, 2012), particularly through variations in localised disturbance (e.g. grazing pressure), vegetation structure, soil type (Barton et al., 2016; Hoffmann, 2000), and microclimatic conditions (Barton et al., 2016; Gibb, 2012). The spatial arrangement and amount of habitat can also have a strong influence on habitat-specialist insects (Driscoll, 2008; Driscoll et al., 2010) and in some cases, random compositional drift is also possible. The combination of these forces likely contribute to heterogeneity of ant communities in these less disturbed sites. These contrast with the frequently disturbed crop and rested paddocks that generate more homogenous communities. Protection of remnant vegetation and appropriate farm management practices are needed to minimise losses in insect biodiversity and the important ecological functions they provide (De Bruyn, 1999; Samways et al., 2020; Yates et al., 2012).

Increased similarity in community composition between restoration plantings and their adjacent remnant patches provides evidence that native plantings are an effective restoration tool for ant communities over relatively short periods (< 7 years). We also found greater community dispersion when farmlands are restored with native plantings, indicating that restoration can increase ant community heterogeneity. This finding is in agreement with studies on the ability of ant communities to rapidly recover following revegetation of farmlands through the provisioning of habitat structure and resources similar to remnant patches (Colloff et al., 2010; Gibb and Cunningham, 2013; Lomov et al., 2009). In our study landscape, recently established plantings are associated with increased habitat complexity from native trees and shrubs (Eucalyptus, Acacia) and increased ground-layer from the exclusion of livestock (Ng et al., 2018b), which are features that are characteristic of remnant patches. These features provide a combination of plant sugar resources, suitable nesting habitats and microclimatic conditions critical for many ant species (Gibb, 2012). While we demonstrate that revegetation adjacent to remnant vegetation can lead to rapid recovery of ant communities, an important next question to address is whether the same benefits arise from revegetation that is not adjacent to a source of potential colonists. Reintroductions may be necessary in more isolated plantings.

Iridomyrmex purpureus was an indicator species for remnant patches in our study, and was five times more likely to occur in the remnant patches than farmlands. Many Iridomyrmex species are woodland specialists that are disadvantaged by agricultural disturbance (Abensperg-Traun et al., 1996; Hoffmann, 2000; Majer, 1976) because they depend on nectar and scale insect exudate found on native shrubs and trees (Barton et al., 2016; Davidson et al., 2004). Species of Iridomyrmex can also be highly aggressive and dominate other ant species (Andersen, 1993; Greenslade, 1976), and aggressive species in other taxa have a profound influence on community composition (Driscoll and Lindenmayer, 2010). We therefore speculate that the presence of Iridomyrmex in remnant vegetation may have an important role in driving the observed community divergence, and conversely, that its loss allowed homogenisation and changes to community structure in the cropped and rested paddocks.

This dominant Iridomyrmex ant species appears to provide opportunities for a diverse range of communities to establish across different remnant patches. After vegetation clearing and the environmental exclusion of dominant Iridomyrmex however, opportunist species such as Pheidole sp. and Nylanderia sp. (Barton et al., 2016; Hoffmann and Andersen, 2003) may be able to dominate this new environment, driving homogenisation of the ant community. Similarly, the opportunist species Monomorium sp. R1 and Rhytidoponera nr. victoriae were only found in the crop, where the latter is a cosmopolitan genus characteristic of disturbed areas with low diversity (Andersen, 1997; Hoffmann and Andersen, 2003). The divergence in community composition between crop/rested farmland and adjacent remnant patches may therefore be explained by environmental limits that exclude the dominant Iridomyrmex species from farmlands, potentially enabling more generalist species to dominate farmlands. The competitive influence of the observed opportunist species in farmland and their role in determining ant community structure are, however, unclear and need further investigation, as is the precise mechanism by which Iridomyrmex presence allows divergent communities to form.

Species richness was unchanged between the different land uses (both the remnant patch and the different farmland types) in our study, with one species (I. purpureus) showing higher occurrence in the remnant patch. Multivariate approaches accounting for habitat differences were important in further teasing out changes in ant community composition to land use effects. Two species (Pheidole sp. P2 pyriformis gp. and Nylanderia sp. A), were found to be indicators of farmlands (all types) and contributed significantly to compositional differences between the farmland and remnant patch. Our findings reinforce previous assertions on the low utility of broad measures of species richness in uncovering ant responses to land use changes, with many studies determining species composition to be more consistently sensitive to soil and vegetation changes associated with land management (Andersen and Majer, 2004; Barton et al., 2016; Dalle Laste et al., 2019; Hoffmann, 2010;de Castro Solar et al., 2016).

Overlaps of over 30 % of species at the interface between the farmlands and their adjoining remnant patches show that a proportion of species were able to use both the farmland and remnant patch habitats. The majority of these species are native and it is notable that some native species were able to use farmlands. For example, Nylanderia sp. A and Pheidole sp. P2 pyriformis gp. were found in all habitats, but being opportunist species that prefer open areas (Barton et al., 2016), they showed stronger association with the farmland than the adjacent remnant patch in our study. Farmlands can potentially provide extensive habitat for opportunistic species, ensuring persistence of at least a proportion of native species in these highly modified landscapes (Driscoll and Weir, 2005; Ng et al., 2017).

5. Conclusion

We conclude that land use intensification led to homogenisation of the ant community, with loss of species that depend on elements of native vegetation and expansion of generalist and disturbance-preferring species. We found that many ant species were dependent on native woodland vegetation, with mixed cropping-grazing farmlands exhibiting lower variability in ant community composition than remnant patches. We further suggest the association between native vegetation losses and the loss of biotic influence of dominant Iridomyrmex species as a possible driver of homogenisation of ant community assemblage.

Our findings underscore the importance of retaining native vegetation as current intensive mixed cropping-grazing practices appear to be unsympathetic to many ant species and risks biotic homogenisation. Besides retaining remnant patches within a heterogeneous mix of modified land use types, planting native trees and shrubs in farmlands can have positive impacts on ant communities over relatively short time scales, and is a simple remedy to potential insect declines. This discovery provides substantial encouragement for investing in habitat restoration, especially where this can be undertaken adjacent to remnant native vegetation.
